    "#### 2b.5 Evaluating the Accuracy of R_0 Estimation\n",
    "\n",
    "The optimal method to determine the accuracy of a fit of a model is by evaluating the Coefficient of Determination $R^2$. However, there is contradictory information regarding the reliabiliy of $R^2$ calulated using linear method on a non-linear model.\n",
    "\n",
    "Here we use a specific methods to determine the Coefficient of Determination that is specifically built for exponential model that utilizes Kullback-Leibler (KL) Divergence (Measuring discrepency between perfect data and the fitted model) and then use Proportionate Reduction Logic (1 - Proportion, the Proportion increased as uncertainty goes up).\n",
    "\n",
    "1. Determine the KL Divergence \n",
    "\n",
    "$$K(y, \\mu) = -2 \\sum \\left[ \\log\\left(\\frac{y}{\\mu}\\right) + \\frac{y - \\mu}{\\mu} \\right]$$\n",
    "\n",
    "$y$ : Your actual data\n",
    "\n",
    "$\\mu$ : Your predicted data (with exponentinal model)\n",
    "\n",
    "2. Calculate Null Model \n",
    "\n",
    "Null Model shows how much the exponential model actuall helps in capturing data. Null Model assume that number of cases is not growing or changing by just an average $\\bar{y}$ of all data that is collected.\n",
    "\n",
    "$$K(y, \\mu_0) = -2 \\sum \\left[ \\log\\left(\\frac{y}{\\mu_0}\\right) + \\frac{y - \\mu_0}{\\mu_0} \\right]$$\n",
    "\n",
    "3. Calculate R_L (R^2 Value)\n",
    "\n",
    "$$R_L = 1 - \\frac{K(y, \\mu)}{K(y, \\mu_0)}$$\n",
    "\n",
    "If $R_L$'s value is closer to 1, it indicate that the model is more accurate or nearly captures almost all the information avaiable in the data.\n",
    "\n",
    "This method of determining $R_L$ score is derived from \"A R-squared measure of goodness of fit for some common nonlinear regression models\" (Cameron & Windmeijer, 1995)"
   ]
  },
